07332nam a22010455i 9783110752908DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021952437  a97831107529087 a10.1515/97831107529082doi  a(DE-B1597)584709  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aBS2665.304a227.10722300aKarl Barth's Epistle to the Romans :bRetrospect and Prospect /ced. by Christophe Chalamet, Andreas Dettwiler, Sarah Stewart-Kroeker. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (VIII, 495 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTheologische Bibliothek Töpelmann ,x0563-4288 ;v1960 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aKarl Barth's commentary on Paul's epistle to the Romans, in its two editions (1919 and 1922), is one of the most significant works published in Christian theology in the 20th century. This book, which landed "like a bombshell on the theologians' playground," still deserves close scrutiny one hundred years after its publication.In this volume, New Testament scholars, philosophers of religion and systematic theologians ponder the intricacies of Barth's "expressionistic" commentary, pointing out the ways in which Barth interprets Paul's epistle for his own day, how this actualized interpretation of the apostle's message challenged the theology of Barth's time, and how some of the insights he articulated in 1919 and in 1922 have shaped Christian theology up to our day. With his commentary, the young Swiss pastor paved the way for a renewed, intensely theological interpretation of the Scriptures.The volume thus centers of some of the key themes which run through Barth's commentary: faith as divine gift beyond any human experience or psychological data, the Easter event as the turning point of the world's history, God's judgment and mercy and God's one Word in Jesus Christ.This volume represents a major contribution to the interpretation of Karl Barth's early thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aTheology, Doctrinal. 4aDialektische Theologie. 4aKarl Barth. 4aRömerbrief. 4atheologische Hermeneutik.  aEpistle to the Romans.  aKarl Barth.  adialectical theology.  atheological and philosophical hermeneutics.1 aAskani, Hans-Christoph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarclay, John M.G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBourgine, Benoît, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChalamet, Christophe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChalamet, Christophe, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDermange, François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDettwiler, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDettwiler, Andreas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aElliott, Mark W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeneuil, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaventa, Beverly Roberts, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGisel, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGockel, Matthias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrondin, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJaillet, Elio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaltwasser, Cambria